<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,150,465]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,331,357]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks</emphasis>
: This species is poorly documented in South African waters and any specimens collected should be retained. A deep-sea Stingray (
<taxonomicName box="[546,758,367,393]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Plesiobatidae" genus="Plesiobatis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Myliobatiformes" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="davisei">
<emphasis box="[546,758,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Plesiobatis davisei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) was once caught off northern KZN with bite wounds from this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Ebert" box="[341,540,403,429]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Ebert" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="355 - 357" refId="ref99310" refString="Ebert, D. A., Cowley, P. D. &amp; Compagno, L. J. V. (2002) First records of the longnose spiny dogfish, Squalus blainvillei (Squalidae) and deep-water stingray, Plesiobatis daviesi (Urolophidae) from South African waters. South African Journal of Marine Science, 24, 355 - 357. https: // doi. org / 10.2989 / 025776102784528538" type="journal article" year="2002">
Ebert 
<emphasis box="[410,459,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al</emphasis>
., 2002
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ebert D. A." box="[551,685,403,429]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref98340" refString="Ebert D. A. (2013) Deep-sea cartilaginous fishes of the Indian Ocean. Vol. 1. Sharks. FAO Species Catalogue for Fishery Purposes No. 8. Vol. 1. FAO, Rome, 256 pp." type="book" year="2013">Ebert, 2013</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ebert D. A." box="[696,757,403,429]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" refId="ref98383" refString="Ebert D. A. (2014) Deep-sea cartilaginous fishes of the Indian Ocean. Vol. 2. Batoids and chimaeras. FAO Species Catalogue for Fishery Purposes No. 8. Vol. 2. FAO, Rome, 129 pp." type="book" year="2014">2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
